ALGORITHM CHARACTERISTICS\
In this section, the two most important characteristics of the algorithm, biasing radius and\
biasing ratio, are explained in detail with tabular examples to give a better understanding of\
how the two factors affect the efficiency of the algorithm.\

\fs19\fsmilli9970 BIASING RADIUS\

\fs24\fsmilli12012 Biasing radius is the radius of sphere within which biasing takes place around Z
\fs16\fsmilli8048 beacon
\fs24\fsmilli12012 . The radius\
R
\fs16\fsmilli8048 beacon
\fs24\fsmilli12012  
\fs24 can be chosen according to the planner\'92s requirements. For a relatively larger R
\fs16\fsmilli8048 beacon
\fs24\fsmilli12012  in\
a configuration Space, the path has a greater chance of moving quickly towards an optimum\
path as the biasing starts, and as the iterations continue, the convergence rate slows down. On\
the other hand, when the radius R
\fs16\fsmilli8048 beacon
\fs24\fsmilli12012  is kept small for the same configuration space, the\
convergence rate of the path towards an optimum path will be slower as the biasing starts but\
once an optimum enough path is found, it is certain to reach an optimized path and also at a\
faster rate towards the end as compared to when the radius R
\fs16\fsmilli8048 beacon 
\fs24\fsmilli12012 was kept large.\
This might be seen as a trade off between the planning time and the navigation time. If,\
for example, a motion planning and navigation problem are put up, which could be solved by\
using this algorithm and which is more concerned about reducing planning time rather than\
navigation time, then the better solution is a larger radius and vice versa. However, there is a\

\fs24 limit to increasing the radius as if it is increased to a large value, the algorithm\'92s behaviour\

\fs24\fsmilli12012 becomes identical to that of RRT*\
. For one of the many environments used for\
experimentation, the experimental results for various biasing radius vs number of iterations to\
